    "summary": "I am an Associate Professor at the Institute of Political Science of Leiden University. My current research project, financed by an NWO Veni grant, addresses the question why small states have more stable political systems than large ones, despite strongly personalized politics and the weakness of political structures. I am conducting this research partially at the Royal Netherlands Institute of Southeast Asian and Caribbean Studies (KITLV). \n\nI obtained my PhD at Leiden University in 2014. My PhD-research, which was published as a monograph with Routledge, focuses on democratic development in microstates. In the context of my PhD, I have carried out field analysis in San Marino, Saint Kitts and Nevis, Seychelles, and Palau. My PhD thesis won the 2014 Annual Thesis Prize of the Dutch and Flemish Political Science Associations (NKWP).\n\nFrom 2014 to 2016, I worked as a postdoctoral researcher at KITLV, where I studied the six Dutch Caribbean islands as part of the NWO-funded project 'Confronting Caribbean Challenges'. In this project, I analyzed the effects of the 2010 constitutional reform of the Dutch Caribbean islands on local political and democratic development, as well as politics in other non-sovereign territories. \n\nMy research has been published in renowned journals of comparative political science, among which Comparative Politics, Comparative Political Studies, Democratization, Geopolitics, the Journal of Democracy, Party Politics,and Publius: the Journal of Federalism. In 2017, my new book on democratization in small states will be published with Oxford University Press (co-authored with Jack Corbett). \n\nAreas of expertise: small states, comparative politics, democracy & democratization, informal politics, political institutions.",
